
[1]emerald

   EM'ERALD, n. [L. smaragdus.] A mineral and a precious stone, whose
   colors are a pure, lively green, varying to a pale,yellowish, bluish,
   or grass green. It is always crystallized, and almost always appears in
   regular, hexahedral prisms, more or less perfect, and sometimes
   slightly modified by truncations on the edges, or on the solid angles.
   It is a little harder than quartz, becomes electric by friction, is
   often transparent, sometimes only translucent, and before the blowpipe
   is fusible into a whitish enamel or glass. The finest emeralds have
   been found in Peru.

   The subspecies of emerald are the precious emerald and the beryl.
